# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-druid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Druid is commonly used in business intelligence-OLAP applications to analyze high volumes of real-time and historical data.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Druid is used in production by technology companies such as Alibaba, Airbnb, Nielsen, Cisco, eBay, Lyft, Netflix, PayPal, Pinterest, Reddit, Twitter, Walmart, Wikimedia Foundation and Yahoo.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Druid was started in 2011 by Eric Tschetter, Fangjin Yang, Gian Merlino and Vadim Ogievetsky to power the analytics product of Metamarkets.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] The project was open-sourced under the GPL license in October 2012, and moved to an Apache License in February 2015.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Fully deployed, Druid runs as a cluster of specialized processes (called nodes in Druid) to support a fault-tolerant architecture where data is stored redundantly, and there is no single point of failure.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] The cluster includes external dependencies for coordination (Apache ZooKeeper), metadata storage (e.g.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] MySQL, PostgreSQL, or Derby), and a deep storage facility (e.g.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] HDFS, or Amazon S3) for permanent data backup.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Client queries first hit broker nodes, which forward them to the appropriate data nodes (either historical or real-time).
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Since Druid segments may be partitioned, an incoming query can require data from multiple segments and partitions (or shards) stored on different nodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Brokers are able to learn which nodes have the required data, and also merge partial results before returning the aggregated result.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Operations relating to data management in historical nodes are overseen by coordinator nodes.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Apache ZooKeeper is used to register all nodes, manage certain aspects of internode communications, and provide for leader elections.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] In 2019, researchers compared the performance of Hive, Presto, and Druid using a denormalized Star Schema Benchmark based on the TPC-H standard.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Druid was tested using both a “Druid Best” configuration using tables with hashed partitions and a “Druid Suboptimal” configuration which does not use hashed partitions.
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Tests were conducted by running the 13 TPC-H queries using TPC-H Scale Factor 30 (a 30GB database), Scale Factor 100 (a 100GB database), and Scale Factor 300 (a 300GB database).
[src:apache-druid/apache-druid] Druid performance was measured as at least 98% faster than Hive and at least 90% faster than Presto in each scenario, even when using the Druid Suboptimized configuration.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:apache-druid/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:apache-druid/data-stream] In connection-oriented communication, a **data stream** is the transmission of a sequence of digitally encoded signals to convey information.
[src:apache-druid/data-stream] Typically, the transmitted symbols are grouped into a series of packets.
[src:apache-druid/data-stream] Most data transmitted over the Internet is transmitted as a data stream.
[src:apache-druid/data-stream] Using a mobile phone to have a conversation transmits the sound as a data stream.
[src:apache-druid/data-stream] 2. $\Delta$ is a sequence of positive real time intervals.
[src:apache-druid/data-stream] Data Stream contains different sets of data, that depend on the chosen data format.
[src:apache-druid/data-stream] A **data point** is a tag that collects information about a certain action, performed by a user on a website.
[src:apache-druid/data-stream] Data points exists in two types, the values of which are used to create appropriate audiences.
[src:apache-druid/data-stream] Information gathered out of websites are based on user behavior.
[src:apache-druid/data-stream] Data providers deliver both personal or non-personal information.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] In computing, **online analytical processing (OLAP)** (/ˈoʊlæp/), is an approach to quickly answer multi-dimensional analytical (MDA) queries.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The term *OLAP* was created as a slight modification of the traditional database term online transaction processing (OLTP).
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is part of the broader category of business intelligence, which also encompasses relational databases, report writing and data mining.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Typical applications of OLAP include business reporting for sales, marketing, management reporting, business process management (BPM), budgeting and forecasting, financial reporting and similar areas, with new applications emerging, such as agriculture.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] OLAP tools enable users to analyse multidimensional data interactively from multiple perspectives.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] OLAP consists of three basic analytical operations: consolidation (roll-up), drill-down, and slicing and dicing.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Consolidation involves the aggregation of data that can be accumulated and computed in one or more dimensions.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] For example, all sales offices are rolled up to the sales department or sales division to anticipate sales trends.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] By contrast, the drill-down is a technique that allows users to navigate through the details.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] For instance, users can view the sales by individual products that make up a region's sales.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Slicing and dicing is a feature whereby users can take out (slicing) a specific set of data of the OLAP cube and view (dicing) the slices from different viewpoints.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] These viewpoints are sometimes called dimensions (such as looking at the same sales by salesperson, or by date, or by customer, or by product, or by region, etc.).
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Databases configured for OLAP use a multidimensional data model, allowing for complex analytical and ad hoc queries with a rapid execution time.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] They borrow aspects of navigational databases, hierarchical databases and relational databases.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is typically contrasted to OLTP (online transaction processing), which is generally characterized by much less complex queries, in a larger volume, to process transactions rather than for the purpose of business intelligence or reporting.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Whereas OLAP systems are mostly optimized for read, OLTP has to process all kinds of queries (read, insert, update and delete).
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] At the core of any OLAP system is an OLAP cube (also called a 'multidimensional cube' or a hypercube).
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] It consists of numeric facts called *measures* that are categorized by *dimensions*.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The measures are placed at the intersections of the hypercube, which is spanned by the dimensions as a vector space.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The usual interface to manipulate an OLAP cube is a matrix interface, like Pivot tables in a spreadsheet program, which performs projection operations along the dimensions, such as aggregation or averaging.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The cube metadata is typically created from a star schema or snowflake schema or fact constellation of tables in a relational database.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Measures are derived from the records in the fact table and dimensions are derived from the dimension tables.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Each *measure* can be thought of as having a set of *labels*, or meta-data associated with it.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] A *dimension* is what describes these *labels*; it provides information about the *measure*.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] A simple example would be a cube that contains a store's sales as a *measure*, and Date/Time as a *dimension*.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Each Sale has a Date/Time *label* that describes more about that sale.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is defined as "a variation of the relational model that uses multidimensional structures to organize data and express the relationships between data".
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The structure is broken into cubes and the cubes are able to store and access data within the confines of each cube.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] "Each cell within a multidimensional structure contains aggregated data related to elements along each of its dimensions".
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Even when data is manipulated it remains easy to access and continues to constitute a compact database format.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is quite popular for analytical databases that use online analytical processing (OLAP) applications.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Analytical databases use these databases because of their ability to deliver answers to complex business queries swiftly.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Data can be viewed from different angles, which gives a broader perspective of a problem unlike other models.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] It has been claimed that for complex queries OLAP cubes can produce an answer in around 0.1% of the time required for the same query on OLTP relational data.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The most important mechanism in OLAP which allows it to achieve such performance is the use of *aggregations*.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Aggregations are built from the fact table by changing the granularity on specific dimensions and aggregating up data along these dimensions, using an aggregate function (or *aggregation function*).
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The number of possible aggregations is determined by every possible combination of dimension granularities.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The combination of all possible aggregations and the base data contains the answers to every query which can be answered from the data.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Because usually there are many aggregations that can be calculated, often only a predetermined number are fully calculated; the remainder are solved on demand.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The problem of deciding which aggregations (views) to calculate is known as the view selection problem.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] View selection can be constrained by the total size of the selected set of aggregations, the time to update them from changes in the base data, or both.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The objective of view selection is typically to minimize the average time to answer OLAP queries, although some studies also minimize the update time.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Many approaches to the problem have been explored, including greedy algorithms, randomized search, genetic algorithms and A* search algorithm.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Some aggregation functions can be computed for the entire OLAP cube by precomputing values for each cell, and then computing the aggregation for a roll-up of cells by aggregating these aggregates, applying a divide and conquer algorithm to the multidimensional problem to compute them efficiently.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] For example, the overall sum of a roll-up is just the sum of the sub-sums in each cell.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Functions that can be decomposed in this way are called decomposable aggregation functions, and include `COUNT`, `MAX`, `MIN`, and `SUM`, which can be computed for each cell and then directly aggregated; these are known as self-decomposable aggregation functions.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] In other cases, the aggregate function cannot be computed without analyzing the entire set at once, though in some cases approximations can be computed; examples include `DISTINCT COUNT`, `MEDIAN`, and `MODE`; for example, the median of a set is not the median of medians of subsets.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] These latter are difficult to implement efficiently in OLAP, as they require computing the aggregate function on the base data, either computing them online (slow) or precomputing them for possible rollouts (large space).
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] OLAP systems have been traditionally categorized using the following taxonomy.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP (multi-dimensional online analytical processing) is the classic form of OLAP and is sometimes referred to as just OLAP.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP stores this data in an optimized multi-dimensional array storage, rather than in a relational database.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Some MOLAP tools require the pre-computation and storage of derived data, such as consolidations – the operation known as processing.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Such MOLAP tools generally utilize a pre-calculated data set referred to as a data cube.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The data cube contains all the possible answers to a given range of questions.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] As a result, they have a very fast response to queries.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] On the other hand, updating can take a long time depending on the degree of pre-computation.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Pre-computation can also lead to what is known as data explosion.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Other MOLAP tools, particularly those that implement the functional database model do not pre-compute derived data but make all calculations on demand other than those that were previously requested and stored in a cache.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Examples of commercial products that use MOLAP are Cognos Powerplay, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy, Microsoft Analysis Services, Essbase, TM1, Jedox, and icCube.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] While ROLAP uses a relational database source, generally the database must be carefully designed for ROLAP use.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] A database which was designed for OLTP will not function well as a ROLAP database.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Therefore, ROLAP still involves creating an additional copy of the data.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] However, since it is a database, a variety of technologies can be used to populate the database.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] In the OLAP industry ROLAP is usually perceived as being able to scale for large data volumes but suffering from slower query performance as opposed to MOLAP.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP Survey, the largest independent survey across all major OLAP products, being conducted for 6 years (2001 to 2006) have consistently found that companies using ROLAP report slower performance than those using MOLAP even when data volumes were taken into consideration.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] However, as with any survey there are a number of subtle issues that must be taken into account when interpreting the results.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Some companies select ROLAP because they intend to re-use existing relational database tables—these tables will frequently not be optimally designed for OLAP use.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The superior flexibility of ROLAP tools allows this less-than-optimal design to work, but performance suffers.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP tools in contrast would force the data to be re-loaded into an optimal OLAP design.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The undesirable trade-off between additional ETL cost and slow query performance has ensured that most commercial OLAP tools now use a "Hybrid OLAP" (HOLAP) approach, which allows the model designer to decide which portion of the data will be stored in MOLAP and which portion in ROLAP.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] There is no clear agreement across the industry as to what constitutes "Hybrid OLAP", except that a database will divide data between relational and specialized storage.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] For example, for some vendors, a HOLAP database will use relational tables to hold the larger quantities of detailed data and use specialized storage for at least some aspects of the smaller quantities of more-aggregate or less-detailed data.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP addresses the shortcomings of MOLAP and ROLAP by combining the capabilities of both approaches.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP tools can utilize both pre-calculated cubes and relational data sources.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores *aggregations* in MOLAP for fast query performance, and detailed data in ROLAP to optimize time of cube *processing*.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores some slice of data, usually the more recent one (i.e. sliced by Time dimension) in MOLAP for fast query performance, and older data in ROLAP.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Moreover, we can store some dices in MOLAP and others in ROLAP, leveraging the fact that in a large cuboid, there will be dense and sparse subregions.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The first product to provide HOLAP storage was Holos, but the technology also became available in other commercial products such as Microsoft Analysis Services, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy and SAP AG BI Accelerator.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The hybrid OLAP approach combines ROLAP and MOLAP technology, benefiting from the greater scalability of ROLAP and the faster computation of MOLAP.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] For example, a HOLAP server may store large volumes of detailed data in a relational database, while aggregations are kept in a separate MOLAP store.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Each type has certain benefits, although there is disagreement about the specifics of the benefits between providers.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Unlike relational databases, which had SQL as the standard query language, and widespread APIs such as ODBC, JDBC and OLEDB, there was no such unification in the OLAP world for a long time.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The first real standard API was OLE DB for OLAP specification from Microsoft which appeared in 1997 and introduced the MDX query language.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Several OLAP vendors – both server and client – adopted it.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] In 2001 Microsoft and Hyperion announced the XML for Analysis specification, which was endorsed by most of the OLAP vendors.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Since this also used MDX as a query language, MDX became the de facto standard.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Since September-2011 LINQ can be used to query SSAS OLAP cubes from Microsoft .NET.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The first product that performed OLAP queries was *Express,* which was released in 1970 (and acquired by Oracle in 1995 from Information Resources).
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] However, the term did not appear until 1993 when it was coined by Edgar F.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Codd, who has been described as "the father of the relational database".
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Codd's paper resulted from a short consulting assignment which Codd undertook for former Arbor Software (later Hyperion Solutions, and in 2007 acquired by Oracle), as a sort of marketing coup.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The company had released its own OLAP product, *Essbase*, a year earlier.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] As a result, Codd's "twelve laws of online analytical processing" were explicit in their reference to Essbase.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] There was some ensuing controversy and when Computerworld learned that Codd was paid by Arbor, it retracted the article.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP market experienced strong growth in the late 1990s with dozens of commercial products going into market.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] In 1998, Microsoft released its first OLAP Server – Microsoft Analysis Services, which drove wide adoption of OLAP technology and moved it into the mainstream.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] OLAP clients include many spreadsheet programs like Excel, web application, SQL, dashboard tools, etc.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Many clients support interactive data exploration where users select dimensions and measures of interest.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Some dimensions are used as filters (for slicing and dicing the data) while others are selected as the axes of a pivot table or pivot chart.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Users can also vary aggregation level (for drilling-down or rolling-up) the displayed view.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Clients can also offer a variety of graphical widgets such as sliders, geographic maps, heat maps and more which can be grouped and coordinated as dashboards.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] An extensive list of clients appears in the visualization column of the comparison of OLAP servers table.
[src:apache-druid/online-analytical-processing] Below is a list of top OLAP vendors in 2006, with figures in millions of US Dollars.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:apache-druid/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:apache-druid/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
